content.text:
Both issues are fixed and typecheck passes.

## 1. Layout squish on md/lg (Custom Providers header)

The header is a flex row: a text column + an "Add Provider" button wrapped in `relative w-full sm:w-auto shrink-0`. The text column only had `min-w-0`, so it never claimed the remaining row width — letting the `shrink-0` button side dominate and squeeze the heading/description into a one-word-per-line sliver. (The "My Models" header didn't have this because its button is a plain `shrink-0` button with no full-width wrapper.)

Fix — `web/src/components/ProvidersModelsTab.tsx:457`:
```diff
- <div className="min-w-0">
+ <div className="min-w-0 sm:flex-1">
```
Now the text fills the row and the button sits at its natural size.

## 2. `Failed to save provider: SyntaxError: JSON.parse: unexpected character`

`fetchJson` in `web/src/lib/provider-models.ts` called `response.json()` directly. When the provider's base URL returns a `200` with a non-JSON body (an HTML error page, an empty response, or the dev proxy serving `index.html`), `response.json()` throws that cryptic parse error, which bubbled up as the save failure.

Fix — read the body as text and parse it safely with an actionable message:
```ts
const text = await response.text();
try {
  return JSON.parse(text);
} catch {
  const snippet = text.trim().slice(0, 120).replace(/\s+/g, " ");
  throw new Error(
    `Expected JSON from ${url} but got ${snippet ? `a non-JSON response ("${snippet}…")` : "an empty response"}. Check the base URL.`,
  );
}
```

So instead of a raw `SyntaxError`, the user now sees e.g. *"Expected JSON from … but got a non-JSON response ("<!DOCTYPE html>…"). Check the base URL."* — which points at the real problem (a wrong/unreachable base URL).

